# Burnout Before It Breaks

A preventive wellbeing learning experience designed to help employees recognize early signs of burnout and take action before stress escalates into sustained exhaustion.

## Project Overview

Burnout is often addressed only after it has significantly impacted wellbeing, engagement, and performance. This project explores how instructional design can support earlier intervention through self-awareness, reflection, retrieval practice, and spaced repetition.

Rather than delivering a traditional awareness course, this solution focuses on helping learners identify personal burnout signals, build recovery habits, and create a practical prevention plan over time.

## Problem Statement

Employees frequently recognize burnout only after symptoms become severe. Traditional wellbeing training often provides information about burnout but rarely supports sustained behavior change.

This project was designed to answer the question:

**How might we help learners recognize and respond to burnout signals before reaching a crisis point?**

## Target Audience

* Knowledge workers
* Corporate employees
* First-time managers
* Remote and hybrid professionals

## Learning Objectives

By the end of the experience, learners will be able to:

* Identify common early warning signs of burnout
* Distinguish temporary stress from developing burnout patterns
* Recognize personal burnout signals
* Select appropriate recovery strategies
* Create a personalized burnout prevention plan

## Instructional Design Approach

This project was designed using evidence-based learning principles, including:

### Cognitive Load Theory (CLT)

* Content segmented into short, manageable sessions
* Minimalist interface and reduced extraneous load
* Reflection-based activities to support germane processing

### Spaced Repetition

Instead of a single learning event, the experience is distributed across five sessions over four weeks.

Learners revisit key concepts through structured reflection and retrieval prompts.

### Retrieval Practice

Learners regularly recall and apply previously learned concepts rather than passively reviewing content.

### Reflection-Based Learning

The module encourages learners to connect concepts to their own experiences through guided self-assessment and reflection activities.

## Key Design Features

### Personal Signal Profile

Learners build a private record of their own burnout indicators throughout the experience.

### Burnout Prevention Plan

A learner-owned action plan created during the final session.

### Privacy-First Design

Reflection responses are not evaluated and are intended to remain private to the learner.

### Mobile-First Experience

Designed for short learning moments and accessibility across devices.

## Assessment Strategy

This project uses formative, non-evaluative assessment methods:

* Retrieval prompts
* Reflection activities
* Personal signal tracking
* Prevention plan completion

The focus is on self-awareness and behavior change rather than knowledge testing.

## Accessibility Considerations

* WCAG 2.1 AA aligned design principles
* Minimum touch-target requirements for mobile
* Text alternatives for all audio content
* Emotionally safe learning environment
* Flexible reflection activities
* Session resumption support

## Evaluation Plan

The project includes a Kirkpatrick-informed evaluation framework measuring:

* Learner reaction
* Learning retention
* Behavior change
* Organizational impact

Additional learning science metrics include:

* Spacing compliance
* Retrieval accuracy improvement
* Signal profile growth
* Drop-off analysis

